\fs24 \cf2 Sattriya:\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 As the least known and least widespread dance form of the octet, Sattriya most commonly is performed in praise of the Hindu Gods of Krishna, and his love stories [3]. Derived from the state of Assam, Sattriya is known most for it\'92s dance-drama nature, and often is performed as \'93one-act\'94 plays [3]. Due to Assam\'92s proximity to Southeast Asia, and therefore Buddhism,\'a0\
Sattriya was originally only performed by male monks in monasteries [3], but has since involved to include all men and women. Take a look at Sattriya being performed below! \
\'a0\
\'a0\
Manipuri: \
\'a0\
From the get-go, one thing sets Manipuri apart from all the other dance forms: the costumes! With the most unique and vastly different costume of all, Manipuri originated from the state of Manipur, and similar to Sattriya, often depicts Lord Krishna and his love for Radha [4]. Also similar to Sattriya, Manipuri is not very widespread, and it's difficult to find Manipuri dancers outside of India. This dance form is recognized most by the Meitei people of Manipur, who incorporate Manipuri as an important element in milestone events such as weddings [4]. Look at the costumes below! \
\'a0\
\'a0\
Odissi: \
\'a0\
If you watch the video below, you can tell that Odissi has many more bends, curvatures, and "roundness" of choreography compared to the other styles. The head ornaments and waist belt worn are also unique. As we make our way from North to South India, we now stop at Orrisa, where Odissi is derived from. Odissi sets itself apart in terms of technicality as well. It places importance on Tribhangi, or the isolated movement of the head, chest, and pelvis [5]. \
\'a0\
\'a0\
Kuchipudi: \
\'a0\
Now, we have entered South India! Kuchipudi displays a relationship with temples and worship [6]. It's name comes from a village in Andhra Pradesh named Kuchipudi, which is where the dance form originated from [7]. More widespread in it's practice today compared to Sattriya and Manipuri, a Kuchipudi repertoire starts off with an introduction of each actor (a dancer in the dance-drama), and then proceeds to short segments of dance that show pure dance/footwork or facial expressions and storytelling [7]. \
\'a0\
\'a0\
Bharatanatyam: \
\'a0\
Originating from the state of Tamil Nadu, Bharatanatyam is derived from the root words "Bha" meaning expressions, "Ra" meaning tune of the music, "Ta" meaning beats, and "Natyam" meaning dance. Hence, it is a dance form which culminates facial expressions, music, and beats, to tell stories and showcase pure dance elements. Today, Bharatanatyam is one of the most widelyspread of the octet, and is practiced all over the world. Similar in costuming to Kuchipudi and Mohiniyattam, Bharanatyam is known for the mathematical nature of it's choreography, as angles and alignment play an integral role. \
\'a0\
Mohiniyattam: \
\'a0\
Known to be a very sweet and simple style, Mohiniyattam revolves mainly around facial expressions and storytelling, with very few heavy footwork elements. Known to be very beautiful, Mohiniyattam is very feminine and delicate in nature, and is predominantly performed as a solo [8]. Originating from the state of Kerala, Mohiniyattam's name comes from "Mohini", the name of a mythical female avatar in Hindu mythologies [8]. Take a look at this dance style below! \
\'a0\
\'a0\
Kathakali: \
\'a0\
The state of Kerala is lucky to have yet another classical dance from originate from its soil. Known globally for the extensive make up, face masks, and costuming involved [9], Kathakali is a cherished art form that always makes the audience in awe, and very few people in the world are trained in the excellence of this style. Eye movements and showing emotions purely through the eyes is a speciality of Kathakali, and the difficulty of conveying stories in this manner is what sets Kathakali apart from the rest of the octet. Another unique factor is that Kathakali incorporates elements of Indian martial arts into it's choreography [9]. \
\'a0\
\'a0\
So, what's next? \
\'a0\
